recordings.rmk: Response to playback from a presumed male perched <2m in Prosopis brushland with open grassy understory. A second bird with a higher-pitched voice (presumably the female) also gave a mewing call, much like in XC28876, barely audible in the background at about 1:24. After about 2:20, the bird changed perches, and I edited out my announcement between these parts of the cut. The vocalizations in this cut, presumably agitated response to playback, lack the increased pulse at the end of the trill as I have heard in more 'natural' song from mccallii. Moon was 2/3 full and waxing, giving off much light. Lots of vocalizations from night birds this night.

recordings.loc: Skidaway Island, Chatham County, GA USA
recordings.rmk: This whinny was coerced. This call is a defensive call, proclaiming a territory is occupied. It was more to find out if the area still supported screech-owls.  They seem to have since disappeared from this location.

recordings.loc: Skidaway Island, Chatham County, GA USA
recordings.rmk: I placed an AudioMoth autonomous recording unit near a known EASO nest location.  The recorder picked up Great Horned and Barred Owls as well as this alarm call.  As a side note, after an extensive search, deploying 4 ARUs in many places on this island, and at this location multiple times, I have not heard this pair again, and I have been successful finding only one owl presumably occupying a small part  the 16 square miles of this island.  This is an abundance of Barred Owls on this island, but none were picked up where the lone screech-owl was heard.

Recording of a red-morph eastern screech owl calling from a mature sycamore tree right around sunset. Only minor adjustments were made to the recording, including noise reduction and minor amplification; no splits or cuts were made. Calls continued in roughly one-minute intervals for more than 30 minutes. A running creek surrounds vast quantities of open fields/  farmland. Mature trees flank the creek on both sides. This owl emerged from a mature sycamore tree alongside the creek just after sunset, entertained by our calls and flew in to investigate.

Unfiltered recording from my iphone6s+. Heard calling in marshy wooded patch behind our house around 1:15AM. Weather is cool and moist; 53 degrees F, 97% humidity. Sky is clear and bright with stars easily seen. When I first heard the sound, I was indoors at my dining room table; to be honest, I first thought it was a neighborhood cat calling. Once I opened the window, however, I heard the owl's distinctive winnying call.  I walked out onto my rear deck where I recorded about 30 seconds of sound. It did not call again after that.
